1 The Binary Analytical Relation Score (BARS)

Lets say we have a target variable \(q\) that wed like to predict and we have a set of \(N\) features (inputs into a model) \(X=\lbrace x_i | i\in 1,..,N \rbrace\) - \(i\) is an index which labels each variable in the dataset \(X\). If \(N\) is particularly large, lets say a few hundred variables, it can be difficult to choose which features \(x_i\) we should put into our model. Generally, we want as few features as possible for two reasons:

  • Models with less features are simpler (Occams Razor)
  • Models with less features are cheaper to build, both in terms of training time and data collection.

The process of choosing a subset of the \(N\) variables is called Feature Selection.

Three popular methods to perform feature selection are: correlation, mutual information, and shapley values. Correlation is great if \(q\) is linearly related - think \(y=mx+b\) from your algebra days - to a few of the \(x_i\)s in your dataset, but nature isnt nice and often things are non-linearly related. So, if you limit yourself to just the correlation, then you might be missing out on important nonlinear effects which can drastically affect the predictive quality of your model. One way to address the problem of non-linearity is by using mutual information, but it doesnt do so well when there are many different scales present within your dataset - again nature loves to do this to us! One way to address that limitation is to standardize all of your inputs; however, that comes with its own set of issues because mutual information is not scale invariant. Basically by standardizing your data, youre changing the relative mutual information scores between variable pairs which defeats the whole purpose of using mutual information. Shapley values are another way to score features, but they are often computationally expensive, the plots can be rather complicated to interpret, and there is a much already a much simpler method to meaure the impact a feature has on a constructed model - the permutation importance which well discuss a little later.

We currently have 3 problems to solve

  • We need a method which can detect non-linear relations.
  • We need a method which can handle multiple different scales within the data.
  • We need an easily interpretable score.

Decision trees have the capability to learn non-linear functions with the only requirement being that the function is continuous - not a huge limitation at all. Decision Trees also handle multiple different scales without issue which solves 2 out of 3 of our issues.

As it stands we have one remaining problems to solve:

  • We need an easily interpretable score.

1.1 How Can We Use Decision Trees to Detect Non-linear Relationships?

First, we need two models: a smart model and a naive model. The smart model will be the decision tree that we previously discussed, and the naive model will be to always guess the median of the target. Why would we want to always predict the median of the target for our naive model? Since we are guessing, that involves choosing a value for \(q\); since the median of \(q\) is in the middle of the range of \(q\), then there is an equal chance that the correct value will be greater or less than our guess. This choice minimizes the mean absolute error (MAE) of our naive model: it gives it the best chance to be the better model.

\[\text{MAE}_{\text{naive}}=\frac{1}{n}\sum\limits_{j=1}^{n}|q(j)-\text{median}(q)|\]

Why would we want to give the naive model the best chance to succeed? Because, we want to make sure there is actually a relationship that is being detected. Note here that \(j\) is an index which goes from the first data record to the \(n^{\text{th}}\) record - a record is specific measurement of a variable.

Next, well compare \(\text{MAE}_{\text{naive}}\) to \(\text{MAE}_{\text{smart}}\)

\[\text{MAE}_{\text{smart}}=\frac{1}{n}\sum\limits_{j=1}^{n}|q(j)-\text{tree}(x_i)|\]

via the ratio

\[r:=\frac{\text{MAE}_{\text{smart}}}{\text{MAE}_{\text{naive}}}\]

What happens when \(r\) is close to \(0\)? This means that our smart model has outperformed the naive model which tells us that there might be a non-linear relationship present between \(q\) and \(x_i\). What happens \(r\) is close to or greater than \(1\)? In both cases, the smart model is doing just as well or worse as the median model which means that we werent able to identify a continuous function between \(q\) and \(x_i\).

Now weve solve all three of our original problems. However, there are some things to think about:

  • Decision trees are prone to overfitting to data, how do we account for this in our score?
  • What is considered a sufficiently high score for a feature to indicate that we should select it?

1.2 Dealing with Overfitting

In the case of a single feature and target, decision trees work by dividing the feature \(x_i\) into different bins. Each bin also corresponds to a set of \(q(j)\)s. For a given bin, the predicted value is just the mean of the \(q(j)\)s contained within it. The values of \(x_i\) that determin a bins boundaries are chosen such that the variance of \(q(j)\)s contained within a bin is minimized. One choice of bins that absolutely minimized the variance of each bin is to simply assign a single \(q(j)\) to each bin. If there are \(n\) values of \(q\), then there will be \(n\) bins. The tree will exactly learn the training data of \(q\), but it also learns the noise that is present in the measurement of \(q\). The optimal number of bins lies somewhere between \(1\) and \(n\): This is the famous bias-variance tradeoff in action. Now one way to deal with this is to treat the number of bins as a hyperparameter and tune each tree; however, this will slow down our algorithm by increasing the training time of each tree. Instead, lets quantify overfitting by looking at the ratio of the number of bins to the number of data points:

\[\rho := \frac{n_{\text{bins}}}{n_{\text{data}}}\]

The lowest possible value for \(n_{\text{bins}}\) is 1: all of the data points are in a single bin, and the prediction of our tree would just be the mean of \(q\) - low bias and high variance. The highest possible value for \(n_{\text{bins}}\) is \(n\) which weve discussed above, so \(\frac{1}{n}\leq \rho \leq 1\).

1.3 Non-linear Transform of the Score

So far, we have two inputs into the score, \(r\) and \(\rho\). Now, we need to come up with a way to combine them so that:

  • We get a score that penalizes overfitting (\(\rho\)) and relative model error (\(r\)) equally.
  • There is a region around a critical point where the derivative of the score with respect to either \(r\) or \(\rho\) is maximized.
  • The score is bounded between two values - say \(0\) and \(10\).

Since we want variables that contribute to models that are accurate and generalize well, our score should equally penalize variables whose decision tree fails to generalize well or performs poorly when compared to the median model. We also want a score which encourages separation between a high scoring region and a low scoring region.

A gaussian functions fits all of the desired properties since it is bounded between \(0\) and \(1\) for all inputs, and there is a region (around \(x=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\) where the absolute value of the derivative is maximized: this is important so that small changes in the input of the score lead to relatively large changes in the score. Basically in this region, a small change in the performance of the tree will lead to the variable either being kicked into the high scoreing region or the low scoring region.

1.3.1 Starting with a Basic Gaussian

\[\text{BARS}(x;\alpha,\beta)=\beta e^{-\alpha(x)^2}\]

Now requiring that the maximum possible BARS be \(10\) sets \(\beta=10\); furthermore, well set the value of BARS at \(x=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\) to be \(.1\). Anything below \(1\) will be considered a low BARS.

\[10e^{-\alpha(1)^2}=.1\]

\[e^{-\alpha(1)^2}=\frac{1}{100}\]

\[-\alpha=\ln(\frac{1}{100})\]

\[\alpha=\ln(100)\]

Notice that at \(x=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\), BARS is equal to \(1\) and the derivative has a value of approximately \(-6.513\). If either \(r\) or \(\rho\) change by a tenth, then BARS goes up or down by about \(.7\) which is relatively large change as compared to near \(x=0\) or \(x>1\). Now, \(x^2=r^2+\rho^2\); thus, the final BARS is:

\[\text{BARS}(r,\rho)=10e^{-\ln(100)(r^2+\rho^2)}\]

2 Toy Example 1

Consider the function \(q=f(x)\) given by \(f(x)=\sin(x)\) for \(x\in\Big[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\Big]\). We know that on this domain, \(f\) is invertible and the inverse function is given by \(f^{-1}(x)=\sin^{-1}(x)\) or \(f^{-1}(x)=\text{arcsin}(x)\)

First, well setup the dataframe with the synthetic data and plot \(q=\sin(x)\) on the specified domain.

Code 
x = [ i for i-/2:.01:/2]
q = sin.(x)

toydf1 = DataFrame(L"x" => x, L"q" => q)

funcp1=plot(x,q,label = L"q(x)=\sin(x_1)",fillalpha=1.0)
xlabel!(L"x")
ylabel!(L"q")
savefig(funcp1,fileprefix*"functionOnDomain1"*ext)
funcp1

2.1 Calculating the BARS matrix

Code 
Toy1Matrix = barsMatrix(toydf1)
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
22 Matrix{Float64}:
 9.46  9.42
 9.46  9.42
Code 
hmap1 = matrixPlot("Toy 1 Bars",Toy1Matrix,toydf1,0)
#savefig(hmap1,fileprefix*"/hmap1"*ext)
hmap1

Notice that even in this ideal case, the BARS matrix is not symmetric: do note that the values presented are high, but not 10. With BARS such high values basically show that there is a function that exists between \(q\) and \(x\), and the difference between these values is incredibly small. The diagonal elements of the BARS matrix, \(B_{xx}\) and \(B_{qq}\), represent the identity functions. These are included to show a best case scenario for the BARS values for the given data.

The off diagonal elements are more interesting. Looking at \(B_{xq}\), (\(x^{\text{th}}\) row and \(q^{\text{th}}\) column), we see that \(q\) is a function of \(x\). Additionally, \(B_{qx}\) shows that there is an inverse! This confirms what we already know: on the interval \(x\in\Big[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{\pi}{2}\Big]\), \(f(x)=\sin(x)\) has an inverse.

3 Toy Example 2

Now consider the function \(y=g(x)\) given by \(g(x)=\sin(x)\) for \(x\in\Big[-\frac{\pi}{2},\frac{3\pi}{2}\Big]\). In this case we know that an inverse for \(g\) does not exist since such a relation would fail the vertical line test

Code 
x = [ i for i-/2:.01:3/2 ]
q = sin.(x)

toydf2 = DataFrame(L"x" => x, L"q" => q) 

funcp2=plot(x,q,label = L"q(x)=\sin(x_1)",fillalpha=1.0)
xlabel!(L"x")
ylabel!(L"q")
savefig(funcp2,fileprefix*"functionOnDomain2"*ext)
funcp2
Code 
Toy2Matrix = barsMatrix(toydf2)
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface 
22 Matrix{Float64}:
 9.48  9.38
 0.12  9.39
Code 
hmap2 = matrixPlot("Toy 2 Bars",Toy2Matrix,toydf2,0)
savefig(hmap2,fileprefix*"hmap2"*ext)
hmap2

Everything is essentially the same except for \(B_{qx}\) where we notice there is a huge drop in BARS confirming that \(g\) is not invertible
